        "rich_text_8DL9Df": {
          "type": "rich_text",
          "name": "Introduction",
          "settings": {
            "content": "<p>When choosing the perfect piece of jewelry, you might wonder, how many types of diamond truly exist? The question of how many types of diamonds are there in the world has both a simple and complex answer. From origin to atomic structure, this 2025 guide demystifies the classifications and helps you understand the ethical, brilliant choices at <a href=\"https://www.lucirajewelry.com/\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"Lucira Jewelry\">Lucira Jewelry</a>. Let's explore what are the different types of diamonds.</p>",
            "custom_id": "",
            "text_alignment": "left"
          }
        },
        "rich_text_bUfHBT": {
          "type": "rich_text",
          "name": "The Modern Choice: Natural vs. Lab-Grown Diamonds",
          "settings": {
            "content": "<h2>The Modern Choice: Natural vs. Lab-Grown Diamonds</h2><p>Before diving into the science, the most important modern classification is based on origin. The decision between a natural or lab-grown diamond is the first step in your journey, and it defines the ethics, value, and story behind your jewelry.</p>",
            "custom_id": "the-modern",
            "text_alignment": "left"
          }
        },
        "rich_text_JmwFBb": {
          "type": "rich_text",
          "name": "Understanding Earth-Mined Natural Diamonds",
          "settings": {
            "content": "<h3>Understanding Earth-Mined Natural Diamonds</h3>",
            "custom_id": "",
            "text_alignment": "left"
          }
        },
        "image_with_text_pNRQJQ": {
          "type": "image_with_text",
          "settings": {
            "image": "shopify://shop_images/Understanding_Earth-Mined_Natural_Diamonds.jpg",
            "text": "<p>Formed over billions of years under immense heat and pressure, natural diamonds are carbon crystals mined from the Earth. They hold historical significance but often come with concerns about their environmental impact and ethical sourcing. </p>",
            "layout_direction": "row",
            "reverse_layout": true,
            "custom_id": "",
            "image_size_option": "adaptive",
            "show_products": false,
            "products": []
          }
        },
        "rich_text_389YjD": {
          "type": "rich_text",
          "settings": {
            "content": "<p>The journey from mine to market can be long and opaque, making traceability a significant challenge for consumers who value transparency.</p>",
            "custom_id": "",
            "text_alignment": "left"
          }
        },
        "rich_text_Jc4E4r": {
          "type": "rich_text",
          "name": "The Lucira Difference: The Ethical Brilliance of Lab-Grown Diamonds",
          "settings": {
            "content": "<h3>The Lucira Difference: The Ethical Brilliance of Lab-Grown Diamonds</h3>",
            "custom_id": "the-lucira",
            "text_alignment": "left"
          }
        },
        "image_with_text_fwCxtT": {
          "type": "image_with_text",
          "settings": {
            "image": "shopify://shop_images/The_Lucira_Difference_The_Ethical_Brilliance_of_Lab-Grown_Diamonds.jpg",
            "text": "<p>At Lucira Jewelry, we champion a modern, ethical approach. Our<a href=\"https://www.lucirajewelry.com/collections/lab-grown-diamond-necklace\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"https://www.lucirajewelry.com/collections/lab-grown-diamond-necklace\"> lab grown diamond necklace</a> range embodies real diamonds with the exact same physical, chemical, and optical properties as mined stones. </p>",
            "layout_direction": "row",
            "reverse_layout": false,
            "custom_id": "",
            "image_size_option": "medium",
            "show_products": false,
            "products": []
          }
        },
        "rich_text_YAapLV": {
          "type": "rich_text",
          "settings": {
            "content": "<p>By recreating natural conditions in a controlled environment, we offer a choice you can feel good about. This answers the question of how many types of diamond to choose from with a clear, conscious option.</p>",
            "custom_id": "",
            "text_alignment": "left"
          }
        },
        "image_qCzLD8": {
          "type": "image",
          "settings": {
            "image": "shopify://shop_images/Ethically_1080_250_ec90f132-2a6d-4766-bb9d-cfb84b85f608.jpg"
          }
        },
        "rich_text_i38kXp": {
          "type": "rich_text",
          "settings": {
            "content": "<p><br/>1.]Ethical & Traceable: A guaranteed conflict-free origin.<br/>2.]Sustainable: A significantly smaller environmental footprint.<br/>3.Exceptional Value: More accessible pricing without compromising on quality or size.<br/>4.]Unmatched Quality: Often purer and more perfect than many natural stones.</p>",
            "custom_id": "",
            "text_alignment": "left"
          }
        },
        "rich_text_zddNHq": {
          "type": "rich_text",
          "name": "The Scientific Answer: What Are the Different Types of Diamonds?",
          "settings": {
            "content": "<h2>The Scientific Answer: What Are the Different Types of Diamonds?</h2><p>The scientific question of how many types of diamond there are is answered by looking at the presence and arrangement of atomic impurities, primarily nitrogen. This chemical fingerprint divides all diamonds into two main types and four sub-types.</p>",
            "custom_id": "the-scientific",
            "text_alignment": "left"
          }
        },
        "rich_text_xii4nX": {
          "type": "rich_text",
          "name": "Type I Diamonds: The Common, Nitrogen-Rich Variety",
          "settings": {
            "content": "<h3>Type I Diamonds: The Common, Nitrogen-Rich Variety</h3><p>Over 98% of all natural diamonds are Type I. Their defining characteristic is the presence of nitrogen atoms within their carbon crystal lattice. This nitrogen is what often gives these diamonds a subtle yellow or brown tint. They are further divided into two sub-categories, Type Ia and Type Ib.</p><h3>Type II Diamonds: Exceptionally Pure and Rare</h3><p>Representing less than 2% of natural diamonds, Type II diamonds are celebrated for their exceptional purity, containing no measurable nitrogen impurities. This chemical purity is a hallmark of high-quality lab-grown diamonds, like those selected for Lucira's exquisite<a href=\"https://www.lucirajewelry.com/collections/\"> <span style=\"text-decoration:underline\">collections</span></a>. This makes them structurally perfect and often completely colorless.</p><p>If you’re exploring sustainable luxury, it’s helpful to check the<a href=\"https://www.lucirajewelry.com/collections/1-carat-lab-grown-diamond-price-in-india\"> <span style=\"text-decoration:underline\">1 carat lab grown diamond price in India</span></a> to understand how accessible lab-created brilliance can be compared to mined alternatives.</p>",
            "custom_id": "check",
            "text_alignment": "left"
          }
        },
        "rich_text_rGLHMJ": {
          "type": "rich_text",
          "name": "A Deeper Dive into the Four Main Diamond Classifications",
          "settings": {
            "content": "<h2>A Deeper Dive into the Four Main Diamond Classifications</h2><p>Exploring how many types of diamonds are there in the world scientifically leads us to four distinct classifications. Each type has unique characteristics that influence its color, quality, and rarity. Understanding this helps you appreciate the stone you choose.</p>",
            "custom_id": "a-deeper",
            "text_alignment": "left"
          }
        },
        "image_with_text_4wJtbY": {
          "type": "image_with_text",
          "settings": {
            "text": "",
            "layout_direction": "row",
            "reverse_layout": false,
            "custom_id": "",
            "image_size_option": "medium",
            "show_products": true,
            "products": [
              "0-252ct-half-eternity-prong-diamond-band",
              "0-28ct-oval-round-diamond-toi-et-moi-ring"
            ]
          }
        },
        "rich_text_J6zq3H": {
          "type": "rich_text",
          "name": "Type Ia & Ib: How Nitrogen Impurities Define Color and Character",
          "settings": {
            "content": "<h3>Type Ia & Ib: How Nitrogen Impurities Define Color and Character</h3>",
            "custom_id": "",
            "text_alignment": "left"
          }
        },
        "image_with_text_CMwe4G": {
          "type": "image_with_text",
          "settings": {
            "image": "shopify://shop_images/Type_Ia_Ib_How_Nitrogen_Impurities_Define_Color_and_Character.jpg",
            "text": "<p>Type Ia: The most common type of diamond. Nitrogen atoms are found in clusters. These clusters can absorb blue light, giving the diamond a faint yellow or, in some cases, brown color.</p>",
            "layout_direction": "row",
            "reverse_layout": false,
            "custom_id": "",
            "image_size_option": "adaptive",
            "show_products": false,
            "products": []
          }
        },
        "rich_text_EgQbDT": {
          "type": "rich_text",
          "settings": {
            "content": "<p>Type Ib: Much rarer in nature. Nitrogen atoms are scattered individually rather than clustered. This structure absorbs more light, resulting in a stronger, more intense yellow, orange, or brown hue.</p>",
            "custom_id": "",
            "text_alignment": "left"
          }
        },
        "rich_text_RzBjGJ": {
          "type": "rich_text",
          "name": "Type IIa & IIb: The Pinnacle of Purity and Unique Properties",
          "settings": {
            "content": "<h3>Type IIa & IIb: The Pinnacle of Purity and Unique Properties</h3>",
            "custom_id": "",
            "text_alignment": "left"
          }
        },
        "image_with_text_C7TFpy": {
          "type": "image_with_text",
          "settings": {
            "image": "shopify://shop_images/Type_IIa_IIb_The_Pinnacle_of_Purity_and_Unique_Properties.jpg",
            "text": "<p>Type IIa: The purest of the pure. These are chemically pristine with almost no impurities. The majority of Lucira's lab-grown diamonds fall into this superior category, ensuring maximum brilliance and a truly colorless appearance.</p>",
            "layout_direction": "row",
            "reverse_layout": true,
            "custom_id": "",
            "image_size_option": "adaptive",
            "show_products": false,
            "products": []
          }
        },
        "rich_text_M3G3Li": {
          "type": "rich_text",
          "settings": {
            "content": "<p>Type IIb: Extremely rare and famous for containing boron impurities. This element causes them to absorb red light, resulting in stunning blue or gray colors. Uniquely, they are also semi-conductors of electricity.</p>",
            "custom_id": "",
            "text_alignment": "center"
          }
        },
        "rich_text_ADDTPa": {
          "type": "rich_text",
          "name": "Beyond Composition: Classifying Diamonds by the 4Cs",
          "settings": {
            "content": "<h2>Beyond Composition: Classifying Diamonds by the 4Cs</h2><p>While science provides one answer to how many types of diamond there are, the jewelry world relies on the **4Cs Color, Clarity, Cut, and Carat **to define a gem's quality and value. These are the practical classifications you'll encounter when shopping.</p>",
            "custom_id": "beyond",
            "text_alignment": "left"
          }
        },
        "rich_text_FpCiqc": {
          "type": "rich_text",
          "name": "The Spectrum of Diamond Color: From Icy Whites to Fancy Hues",
          "settings": {
            "content": "<h3>The Spectrum of Diamond Color: From Icy Whites to Fancy Hues</h3>",
            "custom_id": "",
            "text_alignment": "left"
          }
        },
        "image_with_text_A3TPFR": {
          "type": "image_with_text",
          "settings": {
            "image": "shopify://shop_images/The_Spectrum_of_Diamond_Color_From_Icy_Whites_to_Fancy_Hues.jpg",
            "text": "<p>For white diamonds, color is graded on a D (colorless) to Z (light yellow) scale. The absence of color, typical of a Type IIa diamond, is highly prized. Impurities like nitrogen (Type I) are responsible for the lower grades on the scale. </p>",
            "layout_direction": "row",
            "reverse_layout": false,
            "custom_id": "",
            "image_size_option": "medium",
            "show_products": false,
            "products": []
          }
        },
        "rich_text_8qAbgi": {
          "type": "rich_text",
          "settings": {
            "content": "<p>Fancy colored diamonds, like pinks or blues, are graded on a separate scale of intensity.</p>",
            "custom_id": "",
            "text_alignment": "left"
          }
        },
        "rich_text_jktLLf": {
          "type": "rich_text",
          "name": "A Guide to Diamond Clarity: Understanding Flaws and Inclusions",
          "settings": {
            "content": "<h3>A Guide to Diamond Clarity: Understanding Flaws and Inclusions</h3><p>Clarity measures the presence of internal inclusions or external blemishes. The scale ranges from Flawless (FL) to Included (I). At Lucira, transparency is paramount, which is part of understanding how many types of diamond are available to you. Every diamond is independently certified by trusted labs like IGI, SGL, or GIA, and our jewelry is accompanied by a BIS hallmark, so you know exactly what you are purchasing.</p><p>If you’re near Mumbai, the<a href=\"https://www.lucirajewelry.com/collections/chembur-store\"> <span style=\"text-decoration:underline\">Chembur Lucira Store</span></a> offers an in-person experience where you can view these differences firsthand and consult our experts about diamond quality, color, and structure.</p>",
            "custom_id": "",
            "text_alignment": "left"
          }
        },
        "image_with_text_WaH4Te": {
          "type": "image_with_text",
          "settings": {
            "text": "",
            "layout_direction": "row",
            "reverse_layout": false,
            "custom_id": "",
